parts.text:
This document (LS7888 Released Document No. 1945, 19444, 19) is a comprehensive list of redaction codes applied to materials released under the Freedom of Information Act 1982. It details various categories of information that have been withheld or obscured from the documents, including personal information (names, dates of birth, addresses, opinions), business information (bank/billing details, internal operations), legal professional communication, deliberative material, irrelevant material, electoral roll material, and information related to the proper and efficient conduct of AEC operations, law enforcement methods, trade secrets, and Commonwealth financial/property interests.

**Relevance to FOI Request LS7888:**
This document is not a substantive record directly addressing the Indigenous Electoral Participation Program (IEPP) methodology. Instead, it serves as an administrative key or legend explaining *why* specific information may be missing or obscured within other documents released in response to FOI request LS7888. Its relevance is to provide transparency on the application of FOI exemptions. The presence of specific redaction categories, such as "Electoral Roll material redacted," "Deliberative material redacted," and "Proper and efficient conduct of the operations of AEC material redacted," indirectly confirms that the substantive documents likely contained information related to the core aspects of the FOI request (methodology design, testing, implementation, and AEC internal processes), which was deemed exempt from full disclosure under the Act.

prompt:
Considering this document as part of an FOI request, summarize the document and its relevance to the FOI request in markdown format. FYI the overview of the FOI request is: FOI request LS7888 sought documents (2018-2019) on the Australian Electoral Commission's (AEC) new methodology for its Indigenous Electoral Participation Program (IEPP), specifically its design, testing, and implementation, including catalysts, tracking, outcomes, Indigenous involvement, and cost/staff. The released documents, primarily emails and internal papers, reveal that the core of the new methodology is the direct matching of electoral roll data with Centrelink Indigeneity data, a more robust approach initiated internally to improve accuracy, replacing less reliable prior regression models. This method helped identify over 107,000 unenrolled Indigenous individuals, contributing to enrolment stimulation events (e.g., 2,646 new enrolments). The documents confirm estimated national Indigenous enrolment rates of 76.4% (June 2018) and 76.6% (June 2019), demonstrating a significant upward trend from previous estimates, though they provide limited information on Indigenous involvement in the design process or the final cost and exact staffing for the project.
